You are given an m x n integer matrix grid and an integer k.

For every contiguous k x k submatrix of grid, compute the minimum absolute difference between any two distinct values within that submatrix.

Return a 2D array ans of size (m - k + 1) x (n - k + 1), where ans[i][j] is the minimum absolute difference in the submatrix whose top-left corner is (i, j) in grid.

Note: If all elements in the submatrix have the same value, the answer will be 0.

A submatrix (x1, y1, x2, y2) is a matrix that is formed by choosing all cells matrix[x][y] where x1 <= x <= x2 and y1 <= y <= y2.
 

Example 1:

Input: grid = [[1,8],[3,-2]], k = 2

Output: [[2]]

Explanation:

There is only one possible k x k submatrix: [[1, 8], [3, -2]].
Distinct values in the submatrix are [1, 8, 3, -2].
The minimum absolute difference in the submatrix is |1 - 3| = 2. Thus, the answer is [[2]].
Example 2:

Input: grid = [[3,-1]], k = 1

Output: [[0,0]]

Explanation:

Both k x k submatrix has only one distinct element.
Thus, the answer is [[0, 0]].
Example 3:

Input: grid = [[1,-2,3],[2,3,5]], k = 2

Output: [[1,2]]

Explanation:

There are two possible k × k submatrix:
Starting at (0, 0): [[1, -2], [2, 3]].
Distinct values in the submatrix are [1, -2, 2, 3].
The minimum absolute difference in the submatrix is |1 - 2| = 1.
Starting at (0, 1): [[-2, 3], [3, 5]].
Distinct values in the submatrix are [-2, 3, 5].
The minimum absolute difference in the submatrix is |3 - 5| = 2.
Thus, the answer is [[1, 2]].
 

Constraints:

1 <= m == grid.length <= 30
1 <= n == grid[i].length <= 30
-105 <= grid[i][j] <= 105
1 <= k <= min(m, n)

Code :

class Solution {
    public int[][] minAbsDiff(int[][] grid, int k) {
        int m = grid.length;          // number of rows
        int n = grid[0].length;       // number of columns
        
        // Result matrix size will be (m-k+1) x (n-k+1)
        int[][] answer = new int[m - k + 1][n - k + 1];

        // Iterate over all possible top-left corners of k x k submatrices
        for (int i = 0; i <= m - k; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j <= n - k; j++) {
                
                // TreeSet stores elements in sorted order and removes duplicates
                TreeSet<Integer> set = new TreeSet<>();
                
                // Collect all elements of current k x k submatrix
                for (int x = i; x < i + k; x++) {
                    for (int y = j; y < j + k; y++) {
                        set.add(grid[x][y]); // insert into sorted set
                    }
                }

                // Find minimum absolute difference between consecutive elements
                int minimumDiff = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
                Integer prev = null;

                // Traverse sorted unique elements
                for (Integer val : set) {
                    if (prev != null) {
                        // Compare current and previous element
                        minimumDiff = Math.min(minimumDiff, Math.abs(val - prev));
                    }
                    prev = val;
                }

                // If only one unique value exists, no pair → diff = 0
                answer[i][j] = (minimumDiff == Integer.MAX_VALUE) ? 0 : minimumDiff;
            }
        }

        return answer; // return final result matrix
    }
}

Time Complexity:

Let:
m × n = size of grid
k × k = size of each submatrix
🔹 1. Number of submatrices

You iterate over all possible starting points:
(m−k+1)(n−k+1)≈O(m⋅n)
🔹 2. Work per submatrix
a) Inserting elements into TreeSet

Each submatrix has k² elements

Each insertion takes O(log k²) = O(log k)
O(k^2 logk)
b) Traversing the set

At most k² unique elements
O(k^2)
🔹 3. Total per submatrix
𝑂(𝑘^2 log 𝑘+𝑘^2)= 𝑂(𝑘^2 log 𝑘)

✅ Final Time Complexity
O(m⋅n⋅k^2logk)
